ce:section.ce:para:
Based on LC-MS/MS results, two possible degradation pathways of MC-LR by UDs were inferred (Fig. 6
                        ). Pathway Ⅰ: free radicals (·OH, O2
                        −) produced by UDs acts as an electrophilic agent to attack the conjugated double bonds (C6 and C7) in the Adda amino acid chain of MC-LR, thereby causing it to isomerize into an intermediate with a molecular mass of 1030.1 [65,66]. Subsequently, due to C–C bond breakage, MC-LR is oxidized into two intermediates, each containing ketone and carboxyl groups and having m/z values of 835.2 and 207.0, respectively. Upon oxidation of the Arg and Mdha amino acids within an intermediate with an m/z value of 835.2, an initial intermediate is formed with an m/z value of 746.6. This process is accompanied by further oxidation and gradual decarboxylation, leading to the generation of two new intermediates with m/z values of 697.7 and 653.2, respectively. Under further oxidation by free radicals, the intermediate forms two different intermediates with m/z values of 610.2, either through decarboxylation of Glu amino acids or MeAsp amino acids. Subsequently, these two intermediates undergo a process of decarboxylation, either of MeAsp amino acids or Glu amino acids, to form intermediates that share the same structure and molecular mass of 565.6. This intermediate is oxidized by free radicals to form an intermediate with a m/z of 526.4, and then undergoes decarboxylation and deamination processes to form two by-products with the same molecular weight (aldehydes, m/z = 482.3) but different structures [67]. Pathway Ⅱ: free radicals oxidized hydrogen on the conjugated double bonds (C4 and C5) within the Adda amino acid chain of MC-LR to form an intermediate (m/z = 1029.5) [68], after which C4 and C5 bonds break to form two intermediates with m/z at 797.6 and 230.3, respectively. Since the intermediate (m/z = 797.6) contains aldehyde groups and forms carboxyl groups under the oxidation of free radicals, the molecular weight of the intermediate increases (m/z = 814.6), and two kinds of intermediates with different structures are generated (m/z = 828.6) along with ArgMeAsp or mha-ala peptide bond breaking. These two intermediates act as acids through hydrolysis to form two intermediates with molecular weights of 517.9 and 331.2. The intermediate (m/z = 517.9) is hydrogenated into an intermediate (m/z = 551.5) and eventually degraded into a product (acids, m/z = 445.1). These results indicate that UDs can exert its photocatalytic degradation function by attacking C4-C5 or C6-C7 in Adda amino acids on MC-LR. Along with the generation of free radicals, MC-LR is continuously oxidized to gradually break its chemical structure, and finally the C-N and C–C structures on it are completely destroyed, and the UDs achieves complete degradation of MC-LR [69].
